TEXT(EV2(<<EOT)); 

Suppose \[f(x) =  \frac{7x-19}{x^2-6x+9}\]

$BR 
Then

\[f(x) = \frac{A}{x-3} + \frac{B}{(x-3)^2}\]
where



A =  \{ ans_rule(10) \} and 
EOT
ANS(num_cmp(7));


TEXT(EV2(<<EOT)); 
B =  \{ ans_rule(10) \}.
EOT
ANS(num_cmp(2));



SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT')); 
$BR $BBOLD Solution:$EBOLD
Since
\[ \frac{A}{x-3} + \frac{B}{(x-3)^2} = \frac{A(x-3)+B}{(x-3)^2}\]
and
\[(x-3)^2 = x^2-6x+9\]
we must have
\[A(x-3)+B = 7x-19\]
for all real numbers \(x\).  Setting \(x=3\) gives
\[B=2.\]
Setting \(x= 0\) gives 
\(-3A +B = -3B+2 =-19\)
or 
\[A=7.\]
EOT


